    <item>
      <title>Ramanujan Summation</title>
      <link>https://archive.enochyu.com/mathematics/2025/ramanujan-summation/</link>
      <pubDate>Thu, 01 May 2025 00:00:00 +0000</pubDate>
      <guid>https://archive.enochyu.com/mathematics/2025/ramanujan-summation/</guid>
      <description>&lt;div class=&#34;theorem*&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;strong&gt;Theorem 1&lt;/strong&gt;. &lt;em&gt;The sum of all natural numbers are&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;$-\frac{1}{12}$&lt;/span&gt;, or &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math display&#34;&gt;$$\sum_{n=1}^{\infty}n=-\frac{1}{12}.$$&lt;/span&gt;&lt;/em&gt;&lt;/p&gt;&#xA;&lt;/div&gt;&#xA;&lt;div class=&#34;proof&#34;&gt;&#xA;&lt;p&gt;&lt;em&gt;Proof.&lt;/em&gt; Let &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;, &lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt; and&#xA;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt; be following sequences. &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math display&#34;&gt;$$\begin{align*}&#xA;    S_1 &amp;amp;= 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_2 &amp;amp;= 1 - 2 + 3 - 4 + 5 - 6 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_3 &amp;amp;= 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 + 6 + \cdots&#xA;\end{align*}$$&lt;/span&gt; Despite the fact that &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;1&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt; is a divergent&#xA;sequence, the following property may apply. &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math display&#34;&gt;$$\begin{align*}&#xA;    S_1 &amp;amp;= 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_1 &amp;amp;= \,\,\,\,\,\text{ }\text{ }\text{ }&#xA;        1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 - \cdots \\&#xA;    2S_1 &amp;amp;= 1 \\&#xA;    \therefore&#xA;    S_1 &amp;amp;= \frac{1}{2}&#xA;\end{align*}$$&lt;/span&gt; Similarly, &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt; may be manipulated.&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;math display&#34;&gt;$$\begin{align*}&#xA;    S_2 &amp;amp;= 1 - 2 + 3 - 4 + 5 - 6 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_2 &amp;amp;= \,\,\,\text{ }\text{ }\text{ }\text{ }&#xA;        1 - 2 + 3 - 4 + 5 - \cdots \\&#xA;    2S_2 &amp;amp;= 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + 1 - 1 + \cdots \\&#xA;    2S_1 &amp;amp;= S_1 \\&#xA;    2S_1 &amp;amp;= \frac{1}{2} \\&#xA;    \therefore&#xA;    S_2 &amp;amp;= \frac{1}{4}&#xA;\end{align*}$$&lt;/span&gt; Lastly, the relationship between &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;2&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt; and &lt;span&#xA;class=&#34;math inline&#34;&gt;&lt;em&gt;S&lt;/em&gt;&lt;sub&gt;3&lt;/sub&gt;&lt;/span&gt; may be investigated.&#xA;&lt;span class=&#34;math display&#34;&gt;$$\begin{align*}&#xA;    S_3 &amp;amp;= 1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + 5 + 6 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_2 &amp;amp;= 1 - 2 + 3 - 4 + 5 - 6 + \cdots \\&#xA;    S_3 - S_2 &amp;amp;= 4 + 8 + 1 2 + 16 + \cdots \\&#xA;    &amp;amp;= 4(1 + 2 + 3 + 4 + \cdots) \\&#xA;    &amp;amp;= 4S_3 \\&#xA;    3S_3 &amp;amp;= -S_2 \\&#xA;    3S_3 &amp;amp;= -\frac{1}{4} \\&#xA;    \therefore&#xA;    S_3&amp;amp; = -\frac{1}{12}&#xA;\end{align*}$$&lt;/span&gt; ◻&lt;/p&gt;</description>
